Subject: [PATCH] net: stmmac: enable the MAC on link up at 10G on 10GBASE-R

stmmac_mac_link_down() clears the MAC's TE/RE bits; stmmac_mac_link_up()
should set them again via stmmac_mac_set(..., true), but its generic
(non-USXGMII/XLGMII) speed switch has no SPEED_10000 case and returns
early. MGBE0 runs 10GBASE-R into a rate-matching AQR113C, so phylink hands
the driver the MAC-side speed -- stmmac_mac_link_up(10GBASER, 10000) --
and the MAC is never re-enabled after a link flap. Carrier still reads 1
(the PHY is MDIO-polled) and the DMA keeps running, so it looks like "link
up, no traffic". ndo_open enables the MAC unconditionally, which is why it
only bites after the cable is pulled.

Handle SPEED_10000 as the USXGMII/XLGMII branches already do; for dwxgmac2
link.xgmii.speed10000 is XGMAC_CONFIG_SS_10000 (0), correct for 10GBASE-R.

Not passthrough-specific. Still present in mainline as of 2026-07-10; sent
to netdev the same day.

--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/stmicro/stmmac/stmmac_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/stmicro/stmmac/stmmac_main.c
@@ -1074,6 +1074,9 @@
 		}
 	} else {
 		switch (speed) {
+		case SPEED_10000:
+			ctrl |= priv->hw->link.xgmii.speed10000;
+			break;
 		case SPEED_2500:
 			ctrl |= priv->hw->link.speed2500;
 			break;
